{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:15:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14080"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:31:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14080"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14080"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.1,0.28,0.14,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"3621"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after missing his scheduled dialysis session. He has a history of end-stage kidney disease on haemodialysis and takes telmisartan for hypertension. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. An ECG shows peaked T waves and a widened QRS complex. Blood tests reveal a serum potassium of 7.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents would NOT help reduce serum potassium levels in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium gluconate","Resonium","Sodium bicarbonate","Salbutamol","Insulin with dextrose"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms of hyperkalaemia, confirmed by ECG changes and blood tests. Immediate management is crucial to prevent life-threatening arrhythmias. While several agents are used in the treatment of hyperkalaemia, not all of them directly reduce serum potassium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the emergency management of hyperkalaemia, but its primary function is to stabilise cardiac cell membranes, reducing the risk of arrhythmias. It does not actually lower serum potassium levels. This makes it the correct answer to the question of which agent would NOT help reduce potassium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin with dextrose\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for acute hyperkalaemia. Insulin promotes the movement of potassium from the extracellular to the intracellular space, thereby reducing serum potassium levels. Dextrose is given concurrently to prevent hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-2 agonist, also promotes the shift of potassium into cells, effectively lowering serum potassium levels. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E can help reduce serum potassium levels, particularly in patients with metabolic acidosis. It works by promoting the exchange of extracellular potassium for hydrogen ions, effectively shifting potassium into cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResonium\u003C/strong\u003E is an ion-exchange resin that binds potassium in the gastrointestinal tract, promoting its excretion. While it does reduce potassium levels, its effect is slower compared to other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing this patient, the immediate priorities would be to administer calcium gluconate to stabilise cardiac membranes, followed by agents that reduce serum potassium levels such as insulin with dextrose and salbutamol. Ultimately, the underlying cause of hyperkalaemia would need to be addressed, and he would require dialysis for definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium gluconate stabilises cardiac membranes but does not reduce serum potassium levels in hyperkalaemia.","Insulin with dextrose, salbutamol, and sodium bicarbonate are effective treatments for acute hyperkalaemia by promoting intracellular potassium shift.","Resonium reduces potassium levels through gastrointestinal exchange but acts more slowly than other treatments."],"references":["Hollander-Rodriguez JC, James F. Calvert J. Hyperkalemia. American Family Physician. 2006 Jan 15;73(2):283\u201390. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2006/0115/p283.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T16:19:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T16:19:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6746"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53641"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type